---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
const reviewed = "July 2026";
---
<Base
  title="Company Formation in Bahrain 2026: 100% Foreign Ownership, WLL & DIFC | ARM Management"
  description="A current guide to setting up a company in Bahrain — 100% foreign ownership for most activities, WLL and BSC structures, Bahrain Bay and free zones, and the incorporation process in 2026."
>
  <main>
    <section class="page-hero">
      <div class="page-hero__bg" style="background-image:url('/images/ed-dubai.jpg')"></div>
      <div class="page-hero__overlay"></div>
      <div class="page-hero__content container">
        <span class="eyebrow">Guide · Bahrain Company Formation</span>
        <h1>Setting Up a Company in Bahrain</h1>
        <p>Bahrain allows 100% foreign ownership for most activities without requiring a local partner — making it one of the most straightforward entry points to the GCC market.</p>
        <div class="btn-row" style="justify-content:flex-start;margin-top:30px">
          <a href="/contact" class="btn-primary">Speak With a Senior Advisor →</a>
          <a href="/services/company-formation" class="btn-secondary">Company Formation Services</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section section--warm">
      <div class="container--narrow">
        <div class="guide-meta reveal">
          <span><strong>Last reviewed:</strong> {reviewed}</span>
          <span><strong>Primary sources:</strong>
            <a href="https://www.moic.gov.bh" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ministry of Industry &amp; Commerce (MOIC)</a>,
            <a href="https://www.sijilat.bh" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Sijilat — Bahrain Business Registration</a>,
            <a href="https://www.bahrainedb.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Bahrain EDB</a>
          </span>
        </div>

        <div class="prose">
          <p class="reveal lede">Bahrain is arguably the most foreign-investor-friendly GCC jurisdiction for business setup. No local partner is required for most commercial and professional activities, registration is fully online through the Sijilat portal, and a company can be legally active in as little as one to two weeks. For financial services, the Central Bank of Bahrain (CBB) regulates a broad range of licensed activity categories.</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">Key facts for 2026</h2>
          <div class="rate-table reveal">
            <table>
              <thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Detail</th></tr></thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr><td>Corporate tax</td><td>0% (no corporate income tax for most entities)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>VAT</td><td>10% (standard rate since January 2022)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Foreign ownership</td><td>100% for most activities (no local partner required)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Minimum capital (WLL)</td><td>BHD 20,000 (≈ USD 53,000) recommended; no statutory minimum for most activities</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Registration portal</td><td>Sijilat (fully online)</td></tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <h2 class="reveal">Corporate structures</h2>
          <p class="reveal">The most common vehicle for foreign investors is the <strong>WLL</strong> (With Limited Liability Company), which requires a minimum of two shareholders and offers limited liability with no mandatory local ownership. A <strong>Single Person Company (SPC)</strong> allows a sole foreign owner. For larger enterprises or those seeking listing, the <strong>BSC (Bahrain Shareholding Company)</strong> — either closed or public — applies. Foreign companies can also establish a <strong>branch</strong> or a <strong>representative office</strong>, the latter being non-trading.</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">Financial services — CBB licensing</h2>
          <p class="reveal">Bahrain has the GCC's most developed financial services regulatory framework outside the UAE. The Central Bank of Bahrain regulates banks (retail, wholesale, Islamic), investment firms, insurance, capital market operators, and fintech companies. Bahrain's <strong>fintech sandbox</strong> (administered by the CBB) allows fintech startups to test services under a regulatory umbrella before full licensing. CBB licensing timelines range from 3 months for a simple investment firm to 12+ months for a bank.</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">Bahrain International Investment Park (BIIP) and free zones</h2>
          <p class="reveal">Bahrain's BIIP and the Bahrain Logistics Zone offer land, warehousing and light industrial facilities with 100% foreign ownership, full profit repatriation and 10-year tax holidays (Bahrain's zero corporate tax already applies nationally, so the additional benefit is mainly in customs and infrastructure terms). The <strong>Bahrain Bay</strong> development hosts a cluster of financial and professional services firms in a premium office environment.</p>

          <h2 class="reveal">The incorporation process</h2>
          <ul class="reveal">
            <li>Check activity eligibility — most commercial and professional activities are open to 100% foreign ownership via Sijilat; a small number (e.g. certain retail, oil distribution) require prior approval.</li>
            <li>Register online through the <strong>Sijilat portal</strong>: reserve the trade name, select the legal structure, upload shareholder documents (passport copies, proof of address).</li>
            <li>Obtain a Commercial Registration (CR) number — typically within 1–3 business days for standard activities.</li>
            <li>Open a corporate bank account; most Bahraini banks require the CR before opening.</li>
            <li>Register for VAT with the National Bureau for Revenue (NBR) if annual taxable turnover exceeds BHD 37,500.</li>
            <li>Obtain sector approvals if required (CBB for financial services, MOIC for specific regulated activities).</li>
            <li>Apply for a Unified Number from the Labour Market Regulatory Authority (LMRA) for employee visa processing.</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="callout reveal">
            <strong>Why Bahrain for GCC market entry:</strong> No local partner, no corporate tax, online registration, and a mature financial regulatory framework — Bahrain is often chosen as the holding or regional HQ jurisdiction precisely because it imposes fewer structural constraints than its neighbours. The 10% VAT is the main ongoing compliance cost.
          </div>

          <h2 class="reveal">Frequently asked questions</h2>
          <div class="reveal">
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>Does Bahrain require a local partner?</h4><p>No, for most activities. Foreign investors can own 100% of a WLL or SPC without a Bahraini partner. A small number of sectors — certain retail, utilities, some professional services — retain restrictions. The Sijilat portal indicates ownership requirements by activity code.</p></div>
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>Is there corporate tax in Bahrain?</h4><p>No corporate income tax applies to most entities. The exception is oil and gas companies, which pay a corporate tax on their Bahrain-sourced profits. No general corporate income tax has been introduced as of July 2026.</p></div>
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>What is the VAT rate in Bahrain?</h4><p>10% standard rate since January 2022. Mandatory registration applies when taxable turnover exceeds BHD 37,500 per year; voluntary registration is permitted above BHD 18,750.</p></div>
            <div class="faq-item"><h4>How quickly can a company be incorporated in Bahrain?</h4><p>For standard commercial activities through Sijilat, a Commercial Registration can be obtained in 1–3 business days. Regulated activities requiring CBB or sector authority approval take considerably longer.</p></div>
          </div>

          <h2 class="reveal">Official sources</h2>
          <ul class="sources reveal">
            <li><a href="https://www.sijilat.bh" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Sijilat — Bahrain Business Registration Portal</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.moic.gov.bh" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ministry of Industry &amp; Commerce (MOIC)</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.cbb.gov.bh" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Central Bank of Bahrain (CBB)</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.nbr.gov.bh" target="_blank" rel="noopener">National Bureau for Revenue (VAT)</a></li>
          </ul>

          <p class="reveal disclaimer">This guide is general information prepared by ARM Management and is current as at {reviewed}. It is not legal advice; activity restrictions, VAT thresholds and procedures change over time. Confirm with the relevant authority or an advisor before incorporating.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="cta-section guide-cta">
      <span class="eyebrow is-center reveal" style="justify-content:center">Speak With ARM</span>
